      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read all safety warnings and instructions before use.</strong> Failure to follow warnings and instructions may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury.
      </div>

      <h3>Required Personal Protective Equipment</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Face mask</li>
        <li>Safety gloves</li>
        <li>Ear protection</li>
        <li>Safety glasses</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Work Area Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Keep work area clean and well lit. Cluttered or dark areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not operate in explosive atmospheres or in the presence of flammable liquids, gases, or dust.</li>
        <li>Keep children and bystanders away while operating the tool.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Electrical Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Power tool plugs must match the outlet. Never modify the plug. Do not use adapter plugs with grounded power tools.</li>
        <li>Avoid body contact with grounded surfaces such as pipes, radiators, ranges, and refrigerators.</li>
        <li>Do not expose the tool to rain or wet conditions.</li>
        <li>Do not abuse the cord. Never use it for carrying, pulling, or unplugging. Keep it away from heat, oil, sharp edges, and moving parts.</li>
        <li>When operating outdoors, use an extension cord suitable for outdoor use.</li>
        <li>If operating in a damp location is unavoidable, use a residual current device (RCD) protected supply.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Personal Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Stay alert. Do not use while tired or under the influence of drugs, alcohol, or medication.</li>
        <li>Use personal protective equipment. Always wear eye protection.</li>
        <li>Prevent unintentional starting. Ensure the switch is off before connecting to the power source.</li>
        <li>Do not overreach. Keep proper footing and balance at all times.</li>
        <li>Dress properly. No loose clothing or jewelry. Keep hair, clothing, and gloves away from moving parts.</li>
        <li>If dust extraction devices are provided, ensure they are connected and properly used.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Tool Use and Care</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Do not overload the tool. Use the correct tool for your application.</li>
        <li>Do not use if the switch does not turn it on and off. Have it repaired.</li>
        <li>Disconnect the plug before making adjustments, changing accessories, or storing.</li>
        <li>Store idle tools out of reach of children.</li>
        <li>Maintain tools. Check for misalignment, binding, breakage, and any condition that may affect operation.</li>
        <li>Keep handles and grasping surfaces dry, clean, and free from oil and grease.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Additional Safety Warnings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Only use original Mirka backing pads to maintain tool safety.</li>
        <li>Read the Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) for the work surface.</li>
        <li>If any physical hand or wrist discomfort is experienced, stop working and seek medical attention.</li>
        <li>Only use an original Mirka power supply cable.</li>
        <li>Check the tool, backing pad, power cord, and fittings regularly for wear.</li>
        <li>Clean or replace the dust extractor collection bag daily.</li>
        <li>Always ensure the workpiece is firmly fixed in place.</li>
        <li>Keep hands clear of the spinning accessory during use.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Dust hazard:</strong> Some dust created by power sanding contains chemicals known to cause cancer, birth defects, or other reproductive harm (e.g., lead from lead-based paints, crystalline silica from masonry, arsenic and chromium from treated lumber). Work in a well-ventilated area and use approved dust masks designed to filter microscopic particles.
      </div>

